Whose charm alike the heart can draw , If formed of marble or of straw ; Whether the voice of pleasure calls , And gladness echoes through its walls , Or to its hallowed roof we fly With those we love to pour the sigh ; The load of mingled pain to bear , And soften every pang we share ! — Ah , think how desolate his state , How he the cheerful light must hate , Whom , severed from his native soil , The morning wakes to fruitless toil To labours hope shall never cheer , Or fond domestic joy endear
